{{For|feminist studies as an academic field (not the journal)|women's studies}} {{Distinguish|Feministische Studien}} {{Infobox journal | title = Feminist Studies | cover = | caption = | former_name = <!-- or |former_names= --> | abbreviation = Fem. Stud. | discipline = [[Women's studies]] | editor = Ashwini Tambe | publisher = Feminist Studies, Inc. | country = United States | history = 1972-present | frequency = Triannually | openaccess = | license = | impact = 0.520 | impact-year = 2015 | ISSNlabel = | ISSN = 0046-3663 | eISSN = 2153-3873 | CODEN = FMSDA2 | JSTOR = 00463663 | LCCN = sc76000192 | OCLC = 476420375 | website = http://www.feministstudies.org | link1 = http://www.feministstudies.org/issues/current.html | link1-name = Online access | link2 = http://www.feministstudies.org/PDF%20ordering.html | link2-name = Online archive | boxwidth = }} {{Feminism sidebar|expanded=lists}} '''''Feminist Studies''''' is a [[peer-reviewed]] [[academic journal]] covering [[women's studies]] that was established in 1972. It is an independent nonprofit publication housed at the [[University of Maryland]] in [[College Park, Maryland]]. Besides scholarly articles, the journal also publishes [[creative writing]] (poetry, fiction, and memoirs), art work and art essays, [[book review]]s, political and social commentaries, interviews, and activist reports.
Occasionally, special issues are published on topics such as Chicana Studies; Women and Prison; Women's Work, Social Class, and Socialism; Sexuality, Sexual Violence, and Sexual Identities; Culture and History in the New South Africa; the Body and Healthcare; Rethinking the Global; and Conjugality and Sexual Economies in India.
== History == The journal was established in 1972 in [[New York City]] by feminist academics and activists who were committed to creating a [[scholarly journal]] with high standards and community relevance. This feminist network believed that the women’s movement needed an analytic forum to engage the issues raised by the movement and to bring together the contributions of feminist activists and scholars. Claire Moses was the journal’s editorial director for over three decades, running it alongside a collective of scholars in multiple disciplines and locations.<ref>[http://www.feministstudies.org/aboutfs/people/claire-moses.html Dr. Claire Mh oses].</ref> The journal continues to be edited by a collective, with Ashwini Tambe now at its helm.<ref>[http://www.feministstudies.org/aboutfs/people/ashwini_tambe.html Dr. Ashwini Tambe].</ref>
