Societies or individual [[institution]]s that fail to adapt and [[institutional change|change]] at a sufficient pace are sometimes described as displaying '''institutional sclerosis'''. It is associated with continuity and stability, and may hamper [[economic growth]].

==National level==
The American political economist [[Mancur Olson]], in his 1984 book, "The Rise and Decline of Nations", first offered "institutional sclerosis" as a partial explanation for the divergent growth rates experienced between the winners (with relatively low post-war growth rates) and losers (with relatively high post-war growth rates) of [[World War II]].  In [[liberal democracies]] experiencing continuity and stability, [[interest group]]s form over time and grow to exact [[economic rent|rents]], becoming vested.  The accumulation of vested interests and [[rent-seeking|rent-seekers]] ultimately slows the ability of a government to reform, adapt, and secure perfectly [[competitive market]]s thanks to a related phenomenon studied by Olson: the [[collective action problem]].  This sclerosis saps an economy's dynamism and lowers growth rates.  In liberal democracies with young institutions, by contrast, competition remains perfect and natural economic dynamism and [[creative destruction]] ensue, generating high growth.<ref>Mancur Olson. "The Rise and Decline of Nations" (New Haven: Yale University Press, 1984).</ref>

==Within an institution==
Institutional sclerosis may also be applied to an institution that is effective in changing in some areas but unable to adjust to changes in other areas. Institutions can evolve efficiently either by expanding original goals to meet a changing environment or by including more members.<ref>{{cite book|last=Tow|first=William|title=Security Politics in the Asia-Pacific: A Regional-Global Nexus?|year=2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|pages=49–66}}</ref> At the same time, however, institutions or organizations face difficulties adjusting to new structures or internal policies.

